article.headline: Late 7-0 run gives Baylor upper hand
article.linkText: No. 24 Baylor pulls away from No. 15 Oklahoma
article.story:
NORMAN, Okla. (AP) -- Kim Mulkey-Robertson was carrying around
the offending sheet of paper even after the game was over.

The Baylor coach, through gritted teeth, held up the press
release and read the provocative bulletin-board material --
underlined and in a bold font -- that came courtesy of Oklahoma's
media relations department:

"Oklahoma is the ONLY team in the Big 12 Conference that Baylor
head coach Kim Mulkey-Robertson has not defeated."

Not anymore.

Jessika Stratton scored 20 points and Chameka Scott hit three
off-balance jumpers in the final four minutes Saturday to lead the
19th-ranked Bears past No. 15 Oklahoma 74-67. It was
Mulkey-Robertson's first win in eight games against the Sooners.

"That's all I needed to put on the bulletin board,"
Mulkey-Robertson said, still seething even after the win. "Two top
20 teams and you're going to highlight that?"

Emily Niemann hit the go-ahead 3-pointer for the Lady Bears
(16-3, 4-2 Big 12) to spark a late 7-0 run in the second half and
Scott took over from there.

The sophomore reserve, who's been averaging about nine minutes a
game, was given a chance to play only because Mulkey-Robertson
thought she might be able to slow down Oklahoma's quick point
guard, Dionnah Jackson.

Scott came through, forcing Jackson into seven turnovers and
even adding another option to the league's highest-scoring offense.

"I've just been waiting for my time," said Scott, who played a
season-high 26 minutes. "When my name's called, I'm ready to go
out there and play."

Oklahoma (13-4, 3-3) has lost two straight, including a 69-51
defeat at Iowa State on Tuesday.

The Sooners committed 21 turnovers and shot just 39 percent from
the field in the second half as Baylor mounted its comeback from an
early 13-point deficit.

"I thought down the stretch we did pretty well defensively,"
Oklahoma guard Erin Higgins said. "But they just had an answer for
everything we did."

Higgins led Oklahoma with 18 points on 6-of-8 shooting on
3-pointers. Jackson chipped in with 11 points and nine assists.

Steffanie Blackmon added 15 points and eight rebounds for
Baylor, while Niemann and Sophia Young each scored 11 points.
